<p>The anti-aging peptide market is full of bold claims and thin evidence. Some compounds have decades of research, human clinical data, and well-understood mechanisms. Others have a single mouse study and aggressive marketing. This ranking separates the two by evaluating each peptide on the quality of its evidence, not the enthusiasm of its proponents.</p>

<h2>1. GHK-Cu (Copper Peptide): Strongest Overall Evidence</h2>

<p>GHK-Cu sits at the top because it has something most anti-aging peptides don't: human clinical trial data. Studies in 71+ women showed measurable improvements in skin density, fine lines, and firmness versus placebo and vitamin C over 12 weeks. It modulates expression of over 4,000 human genes, shifting patterns toward a younger expression profile.</p>

<p>The mechanism is well-characterized: stimulates collagen I and III synthesis, upregulates superoxide dismutase and glutathione, promotes angiogenesis for tissue repair, and reduces metalloproteinase activity (the enzymes that break down collagen). It occurs naturally in human blood, declining with age from 200 ng/mL at age 20 to 80 ng/mL by age 60.</p>

