<h2>2. NAD+ (and Precursors NMN/NR): Strong Mechanistic Evidence</h2>

<p>NAD+ is a coenzyme involved in 500+ enzymatic reactions, including mitochondrial energy production, DNA repair, and sirtuin activation. Levels decline approximately 50% between ages 40 and 60. Supplementation (via IV, subcutaneous injection, or oral NMN/NR) demonstrably raises cellular NAD+ levels in humans.</p>

<p>Multiple human RCTs show NAD+ precursors (NMN 250mg daily, NR 1000mg daily) increase blood NAD+ metabolites by 40-90% and improve biomarkers including walking speed, grip strength, and insulin sensitivity. The biochemistry is airtight: if NAD+ decline drives age-related metabolic dysfunction, restoring levels should help.</p>

<p><strong>Evidence grade: A-.</strong> Multiple human RCTs for precursors, strong mechanistic data, established biochemistry. Points deducted because most studies are small and short-term.</p>

<h2>3. Epitalon: Promising Mechanism, Limited Western Data</h2>

<p>Epitalon activates telomerase, the enzyme that maintains telomere length. Cell culture studies show a 29% increase in replicative lifespan. Rodent studies show 12-13% increase in mean lifespan with reduced tumor incidence. Long-term observational data from Russian clinical use shows 28% lower cardiovascular mortality in treated elderly patients.</p>

<p>The limitation: research comes primarily from one group (Khavinson's lab in Russia), independent Western replication is limited, and no randomized controlled trial has been published. The mechanism is solid and the data is consistent, but the evidence base needs broader validation.</p>

<p><strong>Evidence grade: B+.</strong> Strong mechanism, consistent animal data, clinical use history, but limited independent replication and no Western RCT.</p>

<h2>4. MOTS-c: Exciting Emerging Research</h2>

<p>MOTS-c is a 16-amino-acid peptide encoded by mitochondrial DNA. It's sometimes called the "exercise mimetic" because it activates AMPK (the same metabolic sensor activated by exercise), improves insulin sensitivity, and enhances cellular metabolism. In mouse studies, MOTS-c treatment improved exercise capacity, reversed age-related insulin resistance, and enhanced fat metabolism.</p>

<p>The unique aspect of MOTS-c is its mitochondrial origin. It's one of only a few known peptides encoded by mitochondrial (not nuclear) DNA, suggesting it evolved specifically as a mitochondrial stress signal. Circulating MOTS-c levels decline with age and correlate with metabolic health status.</p>

<p><strong>Evidence grade: B.</strong> Strong animal data, compelling mechanism, mitochondrial origin story, but minimal human clinical data published so far.</p>

<h2>5. SS-31 (Elamipretide): Mitochondrial Protection</h2>

<p>SS-31 is a tetrapeptide that concentrates in the inner mitochondrial membrane, specifically binding cardiolipin, a lipid critical for electron transport chain function. By stabilizing cardiolipin structure, SS-31 improves mitochondrial efficiency and reduces oxidative damage from the inside out.</p>

<p>It has human clinical trial data for heart failure (the EMBRACE trial) and Barth syndrome. While these trials target specific diseases rather than aging broadly, the underlying mechanism is directly relevant to age-related mitochondrial decline. Animal studies show improved cardiac function, exercise capacity, and kidney function in aged mice.</p>

<p><strong>Evidence grade: B.</strong> Human trials exist (for specific conditions), mechanism is precise and well-understood, directly targets mitochondrial aging.</p>

<h2>6. FOXO4-DRI: Senolytic Potential</h2>

<p>FOXO4-DRI is a peptide that disrupts the interaction between FOXO4 and p53 in senescent cells. Normally, FOXO4 keeps senescent ("zombie") cells alive by sequestering p53. By blocking this interaction, FOXO4-DRI triggers apoptosis (programmed cell death) specifically in senescent cells while leaving healthy cells unaffected.</p>

<p>In a landmark 2017 study, FOXO4-DRI treatment restored fitness, fur density, and kidney function in aged mice. The selectivity for senescent cells is what makes it interesting: it removes dysfunctional cells that secrete inflammatory factors (the senescence-associated secretory phenotype, or SASP) without harming normal tissue.</p>

<p><strong>Evidence grade: B-.</strong> Compelling mechanism, striking animal data, but from a single published study. No human trials. High cost and limited availability. Needs replication and human data.</p>

<h2>How to Think About This List</h2>

<p>Anti-aging is a field where the gap between marketing and evidence is often enormous. A peptide with 100 animal studies is still in a different evidence category than one with human clinical trials. And a compound sold with testimonials and before/after photos is in a different category than one with published, peer-reviewed research.</p>

<p>GHK-Cu and NAD+ lead this ranking because they have the most rigorous human evidence. Epitalon, MOTS-c, SS-31, and FOXO4-DRI have compelling mechanisms and strong animal data but need more human validation. All six target legitimate biological processes of aging rather than just symptoms.</p>

<p>The practical approach for most people: start with the well-evidenced options (GHK-Cu topical/injectable, NAD+ supplementation), add moderately evidenced compounds (epitalon cycles) if desired, and watch the emerging research on MOTS-c, SS-31, and senolytics as human data develops. Always work with a practitioner who understands peptide therapy and monitors with appropriate lab work.</p>
